### Failure 4: No Pose Manipulation — Person Stands Upright in Riding Position

The person image shows someone standing straight up. A rider on a horse sits with legs spread apart (roughly 45° outward from hip), upper body slightly forward, arms extended toward reins. The current pipeline has zero capability to manipulate body pose. It clips the person as a rigid cutout and places them.

**Why it happened:** This is a fundamental capability gap — the skill has no pose system at all. The pixel-analyzer is an analysis + compositing tool, not a deformation tool.

**What is needed:** This is the deepest gap and requires new infrastructure. Three approaches ranked by feasibility:
- **Approach A (2D shear/warp):** Apply cluster-level geometric transforms — shear the lower body clusters outward, compress the torso cluster slightly. Crude but implementable in pure Python via per-cluster pixel remapping.
- **Approach B (Part-based deformation):** Treat each semantic body part cluster as a rigid piece (torso, upper-arm, lower-arm, upper-leg, lower-leg) and apply independent 2D affine transforms to each piece before re-compositing. This is the same approach used in Adobe Character Animator's 2D puppet system.
- **Approach C (Pseudo-3D projection):** Use the mesh-analyzer concept on a 2D body skeleton — define a set of keypoint "joints" from cluster centroids, build a skeleton graph in vapor-idx, apply pose angles to each bone, project back to 2D pixels. This is the most accurate and is directly enabled by the Mesh Analyzer skill's topology traversal patterns.

