## PART 8: WAVE MODIFICATION / TSUNAMI — HOW ENVIRONMENT EDITING WORKS

Here is the exact pipeline for adding a tsunami to the beach:

```
Phase 1: Zone isolation
  → detect_horizon_line() → horizon_y
  → segment_environment_zones() → water_zone (pixels in y range [horizon_y, horizon_y + wave_max_height])
  → Label all wave clusters in water zone by crest height above horizon

Phase 2: Wave structure analysis
  → Find the topmost water_zone pixels per x-column → this is the current wave profile
  → Store wave profile as 1D array: wave_h[x] = max(y of water pixels at column x) - horizon_y
  → Find foam clusters (ocean_foam) → these mark wave crests

Phase 3: Amplification
  → Multiply wave_h[x] by tsunami_factor (e.g. 8x for dramatic effect)
  → Apply smoothing: wave_h = gaussian_smooth(wave_h, sigma=20) to prevent jagged edges
  → Add secondary waves: wave_h[x] += secondary_amplitude * sin(x * secondary_freq)

Phase 4: Pixel regeneration (cluster level, not full-image)
  → For each x-column: fill from horizon_y to horizon_y + wave_h[x] with water color
  → Color gradient: deep water = darker blue-green, near surface = lighter + sky reflection
  → Wave face (left side): white foam pixels at the curl edge
  → Foam spray: scatter bright pixels in the zone above the wave crest

Phase 5: Physics validation
  → Wave cannot be taller than image height - horizon_y (would go off screen)
  → Foam density increases with wave height
  → Sky reflection in water must update to match new water surface angles
  → Any subjects in the water zone must have splash/foam generated around them

Phase 6: Shadow and lighting update
  → Massive wave would cast a shadow on the beach
  → Compute shadow polygon from wave crest positions + sun direction
  → Darken beach sand in shadow polygon
```

This same pattern applies to ANY environment modification: identify the zone, understand its structure in vapor-idx, apply a parameterized transform to the cluster data, regenerate pixels from the transformed data, validate physics.

